Stakeholders of the All Progressives Congress (APC) in Port Harcourt City local government area of Rivers State have called on the National Working Committee (NWC) to intervene on the crisis rocking the party in the state. Former member of the Hous of Representatives, Hon. Igo Aguma, disclosed this while speaking with newsmen shortly a meeting of the stakeholders in Port Harcourt. Aguma said: “In our open letter to the National Chairman, we stated that we requested the national leadership of APC should take a special look into what is happening in the party in Rivers State. “Before now, the APC in Rivers State was like an a abandoned. So, we started doing what we are doing now so as to call the attention of the national leadership of the party to our plight in Rivers State.” He said there are plots to ensure that the party has no structure in Rivers State, adding that those behind the plot are also working towards ensuring that the APC is not in the ballot in 2023. The former federal lawmaker reiterated the resolve of APC stakeholders in the state, to ensure that Ibrahim Umar and 22 others, were allowed to participate in the congresses of the party in the state. Also speaking at the stakeholders’ meeting, another former federal lawmaker, Hon. Lasbrey Amadi, said the essence of the meeting was to let the whole world know that there is no division within the APC in Port Harcourt City local government area. Amadi, who dismissed the decision of some chieftains of the party in the area to suspend him and Aguma, said those behind the action were characters without weight.